A technically perfect mess with a weak script. The Gemini with Will Smith did not take the criticism seriously
The dystopian sci-fi spectacle Gemini Man boasts an interesting premise - Will Smith will play a younger version of himself in the film. But according to critics, the story is the weakest part of the film. The film will be released in Czech cinemas on October 10.
Henry Brogan (Will Smith) is the absolute top in his field. It kills efficiently and without any unnecessary questions. But one day he decides to hang his career on a nail. Understandably, his employers don't like this, and they send another killer to Henry. The catch is that the killer is Henry himself, or rather a younger DNA clone of him. Can one determined man win the battle over himself? Literally this time.
Three-time Oscar winner Ang Lee should have been a sure guarantee of quality. Although this is his first sci-fi, he has extensive experience with dramatic action films, as he demonstrated, for example, in the above-mentioned Tiger and the Dragon or the western Riding with the Devil. Six screenwriters collaborated on the script. The most famous one is certainly David Benioff, one of the creators of the highly successful Game of Thrones. According to the first reviews, even all this was not enough for a good film.
"Even though Ang Lee is trying to do great things in technical filmmaking, the film itself doesn't have enough character to make it stand out," thinks Fionnuala Hannigan of Screen Daily.
"This disappointing film is less than the sum of all the talents involved in it. The weak script and plot are held together only by the technological magic of the filmmakers," summed up his opinion Stephen Dalton from The Hollywood Reporter magazine.
"Gemini is a case in which a huge amount of work resulted in an incredibly lackluster action film," says Variety reviewer Peter Deburge.
"A confused product born of a bizarre idea," summed up the film in her review by IndieWire's Ella Kemp.
"It's hard to care about one man being the other's doppelgänger when neither is acting human," wrote Nicholas Barber of The Wrap.
