Only children. We are not sure of reproduction, but we don't have to worry
Some words have bad connotations, even if they only convey the state of affairs. The word only child belongs to them. It refers to a child growing up without siblings, but it does not sound neutral. "You know that, an only child," he says without needing to add anything. It is interesting that "only child" carries this feature since long ago, even from the times when expressions like demographic crisis were not widely used.
Today, even people outside the scientific community know that a fertility rate of 2.1 children per woman is necessary to ensure the simple reproduction of the population. It is also widely known that no state in Europe today achieves this value. France and Sweden are the closest to it, but the simple rate of population reproduction is not ensured by European states. (Within the West, only Israel stands out, with a total fertility rate of 3.1 children per woman.) It is a situation made for alarmism. That is why it is not surprising that the Minister of Labor and Social Affairs Maláčová also falls for him: "There are almost as many single children as families with two children," she said in an interview for LN. But she forgot the devil hidden in the detail.
Yes, it is good when the problem is pointed out instead of trivialized or ideologized. Like in Germany, for example, where the campaign for more children easily gets the label of fad (in the style of "even Hitler supported it"). It is good to be reminded that many couples directly plan for an only child. It is good if politicians show the will to remove the obstacles that lead to those decisions (for example, the weak expansion of work from home discourages women from further pregnancies). But despite all that, let's point out one thing.
When Minister Maláčová says that "there are almost so many only children" there is a sprinkle of demagoguery in it. That statement was appropriate twenty years ago. Let us remind you that fertility in the Czech Republic last ensured simple reproduction in 1980 ("Husákovy děti"). Then it dropped to an alarming 1.14 in 2000. But since then it has risen by almost fifty percent, to the current 1.70 children per woman, which is above the European average. It is still not enough for simple reproduction, so the activity of politicians is appropriate. Only with the alarmism can they take a little away.
Berlin responds to public pressure and solves the housing crisis. They will buy 6,000 apartments from a private company
Berlin will buy from the private Luxembourg company ADO Properties SA for 920 million euros (23.8 billion CZK) 6,000 former social apartments that the city sold 15 years ago. In this way, he responds to the pressure of the public, who are rebelling against skyrocketing rental prices. According to Berlin senator Katrin Lompscher for the Left Party (Die Linke), this is the largest such buyout in the history of the German capital. The opposition criticizes the move.
"The intention is to keep rents stable in Berlin and give tenants security," Berlin Mayor Michael Müller (SPD) said in a statement. "At the same time, we will continue the construction of new apartments and we will legally treat the freezing of rents," he added. The municipal company Gewobag will take over the thousands of apartments located in the Spandau and Reinickendorf districts in the western part of the city this December.
According to Jefferies analyst Thomas Rothäusler, the city bought too much. Rothäusler told Bloomberg that, according to his estimate, the housing units overpaid by about ten percent over their book value.
According to the German opposition party Liberals (FDP), the Berlin authorities are contributing to real estate speculation. The FDP said it on Twitter on Friday. The protest party Alternative for Germany (AfD) called the move a "waste of money".
As early as mid-July, Gewobag got back 670 apartments in Berlin's Karl-Marx-Allee street, the weekly Der Spiegel recalled on its website. The council did not disclose the price at the time. The dispute over apartments on the former GDR-era exhibition street was accompanied by protests and filled the front pages of the German press. It has become a symbol of the plight of tenants in large German cities, the newspaper wrote.
At the same time, the German metropolis used to be famous for its low cost of living and low rents. In recent years, however, it has gained in attractiveness. According to AFP, rent prices have doubled over the past ten years, making it difficult for some residents to find affordable housing.
