The vote of the upper house of the Canadian Parliament confirmed a rumor that has been known for several days: Canada is withdrawing the honorary citizenship of the former legend of the fight for human rights, the winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, Do Aung San Suu Kyi. The current leader of Myanmar (Burma), who spent years under house arrest for trying to bring freedom to her country, lost her honorary title for her role in the genocide against the minority Rohingya people.
The decision to grant Suu Kyi honorary citizenship was approved by the lower legislative body a week ago, and the senators have now unanimously supported it. "It is the right message both for her and for Myanmar and for the whole world," commented independent senator Ratna Omidvar on the decision of her colleagues. "We need to make it clear that the accomplices of genocide are not welcome here in Canada - all the more so as upstanding citizens."
The verdict of the Canadian parliament technically does not change anything for Suu Kyi, it is only an honorary title, but on a symbolic level it is a strong message for her. The long-time human rights campaigner's silence on the atrocities that the army of Buddhist-majority Myanmar has been perpetrating for endless months on the Muslim Rohingya minority is intolerable.
The fact that an officially organized genocide is taking place in Myanmar and that Suu Kyi - the de facto prime minister of the government there - has completely failed in her duty to protect her citizens, was recently revealed by a UN report. Specifically, it mentions the names of several army commanders who, according to the investigative team, should stand trial for crimes against humanity committed in actions that - as the report says - "shock both by the horror of their actions and by their enormous scale". According to the UN, Suu Kyi and her administration were complicit mainly by covering up the actions of the soldiers and spreading a protective fog of lies around them - for example, that it was an "anti-terrorist operation".
After Suu Kyi's removal, five figures remain on Canada's list of honorary citizens: Swedish diplomat Raoul Wallenberg, Nelson Mandela, Tändzin Gjamccho, the 14th Dalai Lama, Karim Aga Khan IV, the 49th Imam of Shiite Muslims and Malala Yousafzai.
Developments around the former icon of the fight for freedom and democracy were also reflected by the Canadian Museum of Human Rights, where information about atrocities against the Rohingya and the parliamentary decision to strip her of the title of honorary citizen was added to Suu Kyi's profile. "We have also dimmed the lighting of her photo on the human rights timeline panel and are thinking about replacing her face with a portrait of a member of the Rohingya minority," Canadian media quoted museum spokesperson Rorie McLeod as saying.
The only thing that will remain with Suu Kyi in the current upheavals - at least for now - is the Nobel Peace Prize, awarded to her at the suggestion of Václav Havel in 1991 for her enormous contribution to the fight for democracy. "While Ms. Suu Kyi's current actions are deplorable, her award will not be revoked," Nobel Foundation head Lars Heikensten told Canada's CBS.
