The Supreme Prosecutor renewed the prosecution of the mother who manipulated the daughter against the father
Supreme Prosecutor Pavel Zeman does not agree with the acquittal of the mother, who manipulated her daughter for a long time and disrupted her relationship with her father. She faced charges of abuse and endangering education. The regional court acquitted her of the charges, Zeman disagrees. According to his appeal to the Supreme Court, a similar act can be seen as a criminal act.
The Supreme Court's decision could have a wider impact on other cases. "A more specific definition of such a specific form of abuse can be considered necessary also from the point of view of streamlining further application practice," Zeman's appeal states.
The district court in Svitavy first found the woman guilty last year of abusing a trusted person and endangering the upbringing of a child. She formed a strong, almost symbiotic bond with her daughter, even in a situation where she should have been entrusted to her father.
The result was a pathological fixation on the mother and a significantly negative relationship with the father. The situation marked the emotional development of the daughter, who was even hospitalized. She threatened to harm herself in the event of her father's custody.
The Svitava court sentenced the mother to two years in prison with a two-year suspended sentence. However, the Pardubice branch of the regional court acquitted the woman of the charges in the appeal process, saying that it is not a criminal offense. The same verdict was repeated by the regional court even after the Supreme Court ordered it to decide again.
The regional court noted that situations where one parent manipulates a child towards the other are not at all exceptional. It is resolved in guardianship proceedings, possibly with the help of psychologists or youth social protection authorities. Only in exceptional cases is criminal law the solution.
However, according to the chief prosecutor, the woman committed both torture and endangering her upbringing. "The accused acted in a completely targeted manner when she aroused negative feelings in her daughter towards her father, and purposefully confirmed these negative emotions. With such actions, she not only pursued the illicit intention of limiting or excluding the father's contact with the minor, but she must have been aware that this in the psychosocial will cause negative consequences in the sphere of minors," the appeal states.
Zeman asked the Supreme Court to return the case to the regional court once more. It appears from the appeal that the child is now in the care of the father.
