The Administration of the Krkonoše National Park (KRNAP) has moved the deadline for submitting bids for the second tender for the repair of the Krkonoše Museum in Vrchlabí by three weeks. The original date for opening the envelopes was September 20, said national park spokesman Radek Drahný. The reason for the postponement of the deadline for submission of bids is the reduction of the budget from 110 million crowns to 83 million crowns.
"We are currently working with the prices that are on the market. There has been a change in the budget, this is the price we expect to be offered. If someone submits an offer that will be acceptable, then the work will start as soon as possible," said Drahný .
Compared to the original plans, the start of the renovation of the museum has been delayed by about a year. KRNAP wanted to have a selected contractor for the construction part by the end of last year and start construction work this spring. According to the management of the national park, the European subsidy of 123 million crowns for the project is not at risk.
The KRNAP administration is unable to select a construction company to repair the museum. It launched the second competition this summer, because in the previous tender all the offers of the companies significantly exceeded the expected price of 65 million at the time. The offers exceeded 100 million crowns.
The museum, which is located in the former Augustinian monastery and belongs to the KRNAP Administration, has been closed since autumn 2017. The selected company should provide the construction part of the project. The total costs, including the construction of a new exhibition, are estimated at 210 million crowns. The KRNAP visitor center should be created in the now cleared building by the end of 2021 after the transformation of the exhibits.
The repaired museum with a new interactive exhibition, which should be a story of nature and people settled in the mountains and follow on from the successful exhibition Stone and Life, should serve as a representative gateway for visitors to the Giant Mountains. The visitor center should provide information about the past and present of the Krkonoše Mountains in the most understandable form and motivate people to explore the mountains and protect them. It should also take over the role of a traditional museum. The center will also offer opportunities to organize concerts, festivals, theater performances or lectures in the open air. The plans include the construction of a new entrance to the building, the creation of a research room or a cafe.
