Francis Fukuyama has been somewhat burned by history. In 1992, at the height of the wave of liberalism that followed the end of the Cold War and the fall of the Iron Curtain, this political scientist wrote in his most famous book, The End of History and the Last Man: "What we may be witnessing... is the final point of humanity's ideological development and the universal acceptance of Western liberal democracy as the ultimate form of government."
Twenty-six years later, we are rather witnessing how, from the USA to Russia, from Turkey to Poland and from Hungary to Italy, rather illiberal models are winning and various forms of nationalism and radicalism are thriving. Fukuyama's current ninth book, Identity: The Demand for Dignity and the Politics of Resentment, attempts to cope with the onset of these forces. As his interview by George Eaton for the New Statesman shows, he is rethinking many of his former positions: he argues that the ideas of socialism should be brought back into the public sphere, and Marx was right about a lot. Although at the same time he insists that his thought development is still in line with the position of the nineties and that the critics of The End of History and The Last Man have misunderstood it.
"What I was saying back then was that one of the problems with modern democracy is that while it provides peace and prosperity, people want more than that... Liberal democracy doesn't even try to define what the good life is. It leaves it they see no point in individuals who feel alienated, and therefore group themselves into identity groups that give them a sense of belonging."
In its time, the book The End of History and the Last Man was written as a strong argument against Marxists who saw communism as the final stage of history. When asked how he now sees the rise of socialists in Britain and the US, Fukuyama replies: "It all depends on what you mean by socialism. If we're talking about ownership of the means of production, then except when clear public services are in demand, that I don't think it's going to work. But if you mean redistributive programs that try to address the huge imbalances in income and wealth that we're already seeing, then yes. I think not only could he come back, he should come back. The long the period ushered in by President Reagan and Prime Minister Thatcher, in which certain types of ideas about the benefits of the unregulated market came into play, had a disastrous effect in many ways."
Finally, Fukuyama tries to calm down the current situation and warns all liberals that even the emergence of new, not entirely democratic regimes will not mean the end of history.
