Kovosvit now offers for sale several properties, halls and plots of land that it either does not use or only uses minimally. This also applies to the administrative building, where two of the five floors are used, and not completely. "Part of the long-term restructuring plan is to slim down Kovosvit and make its operations more efficient. The sale of assets is not part of any momentary solution, whether it is for example cash-flow, but part of a long-term plan where we want to devote all resources to investment development," said the CEO.
Kovosvit exports roughly half of its production. Its standard markets are the EU and Russia, last year to a lesser extent Asia. This year Kuchař ranks among the most interesting India, where Kovosvit won an order for machines enabling five-axis machining worth 100 million crowns. This year, the company also exported two five-axis machines for 30 million crowns to China. "Another order of the same volume is under discussion, which we would like to fulfill before the end of the year," said Kuchař. In the Russian market and elsewhere, Kovosvit faces restrictions due to sanctions.
Last year, the company sold two five-axis machining centers to France, a company that is a subcontractor to Airbus. She delivered another machine this May, and she should deliver another one at the end of the year or at the end of 2020.
The company's main investment this year was the transition of heating from steam to hot water for 20 million crowns. Kovosvit employs 500 people, the average worker's wage is 28,500 crowns. The company is looking for casting grinders for the foundry, machinists, turners and electricians.
The company has been owned by industrialist and armorer Jaroslav Strnad since September 2016. The company has a tradition in the production of machine tools. It was founded by Tomáš Baťa in 1939. At one time, the company had up to three thousand employees.
Thank you for the dance! Singer Leonard Cohen's last album will be released posthumously
The album Thanks for the Dance will contain unreleased material and various musical collaborations put together by the singer's son. The album will be released on November 22.
In October 2016, the album You Want it Darker was released, on which Cohen collaborated with his son Adam. He asked him to help him finish each song. In the intimate recording, Cohen symbolically comes to terms with impending death. He died a month after the album's release at the age of 82.
Seven months later, Adam Cohen began working on the materials left by his father. He invited a whole range of musicians to collaborate - Damien Rice, Bryce Dessner, Javier Mas or the singer Beck at random.
"When we came up with the music for my father's words, we used his own distinctive musical techniques. So he's still with us," said Adam Cohen about the album. "What amazes me most about him are the reactions of those who have already heard him. One by one they say that Leonard is still alive," he added.
The first song of the album is the short song The Goal. "I'm almost alive, I'm almost home," Cohen sings in his signature honey voice. He sang about death, he suspected that he would not live to release new material. He also admitted this in an interview with The New Yorker magazine a month before his death. "I'm ready to die. I hope it won't be too unpleasant," he declared.
In September 2018, Adam Cohen published a collection of his father's poetry called The Flame. It will be published in Czech under the title Plamen on December 31 by Argo publishing house.
