The police charged the manager of CzechTourism, Aleš Pangrác, due to contracts for promotion
The police charged the former manager of the state agency CzechTourism, Aleš Pangrác, due to contracts for promotion. Pangrác confirmed to the SeznamZprávy server that he accepted the charges this week. Czech Television (ČT) reported last year that the police officers were examining contracts worth 38 million crowns in the case. According to the police, part of the money was going back to Pangrác, the server writes. In the case, criminal investigators were also interested in Regional Development Minister Klára Dostálova (for ANO), to whose department CzechTourism falls. According to the server, the investigation into the case continues.
Detectives from the National Central Office against Organized Crime secured evidence in this case in the second half of last November. They were, for example, at the headquarters of the Ministry for Regional Development, at the headquarters of CzechTourism, at the autodrome in Most or at the Sport Invest agency. They also took the official computer from the minister's apartment. In the court order to search Dostálova's home, which was previously quoted by ČT, it was stated that in 2016, when she was deputy, the minister made decisions about the expenses of CzechTourism for the benefit of selected persons indirectly and outside of the standard official procedure. At the time, Dostálová declared that she felt absolutely innocent, that she had no doubts, that she could document everything and that she fully cooperated with the police.
According to the agency, it was the fault of an individual. The media previously reported that it was Aleš Pangrác, the former director of the regional partnership department at CzechTourism, who was dismissed due to the results of the audit. This resulted in the CzechTourism agency concluding 48 problematic contracts.
"Yes, they accused me. But I don't want to comment more on that," Pangrác told Seznam Zpravy severu.
