There are up to sixty times fewer insects than 40 years ago
No other animal class is more represented in nature than insects. Beetles, butterflies and other species make up more than half of all life on Earth. But there are increasing reports that the insect kingdom is radically shrinking. Another scientific study on this topic was released just this week, and according to it, the situation is even more serious than humanity has realized.
The study is based on field research in a tropical forest in Puerto Rico, during which American scientists copied a similar survey from 1976. As they write right at the beginning of the report, there are "ten to sixty times fewer insects" in the forest today. It is about the decline of the entire population, i.e. not the number of species, while the research concerned not only insects, but all arthropods. Due to the extinction of insects, the population of other fauna that depends on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs or lizards, also decreases.
The authors of the research relate their conclusions directly to climate change. According to them, the average air temperature in the forest has risen by two degrees Celsius in the last thirty years, and warming has become the driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. According to the author's team, the study shows that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously thought.
A large article about the report was published in the Washington Post on Monday, which presents the new findings immediately in the headline as hyperalarming. "It's one of the most disturbing articles I've ever read," University of Connecticut entomologist David Wagner, whom the paper cites as an independent expert, told the paper.
The extinction of insects also affects Europe. "The decline here is also an order of magnitude," points out Lukáš Čížek from the Institute of Entomology of the Academy of Sciences. According to him, in addition to climate change, it is also necessary to take into account changes in the landscape, which play a significant role in Europe. "It just runs for a significantly longer time here than in Puerto Rico," adds Čížek to explain why scientists could measure such a rapid decline in the primeval forest compared to the 1970s.
Nokia is suing the Brno company over the name Lokia. Moravians believe that people will not mistake us
Nokia filed objections to the application of the trademark Lokia to the Industrial Property Office. However, according to CCV, product confusion is unlikely.
The Brno company developing CCV software is facing legal action from the Finnish telecommunications equipment manufacturer Nokia. Finns don't like that the Brno-based company's warehouse management program is called Lokia WMS, the E15 newspaper wrote. Nokia therefore filed objections to the application of the Lokia trademark to the Industrial Property Office. CCV judges that confusion is not likely.
Marketing director Petr Ondrášek said that two dozen customers are already using the program, it has been on the market since last September.
"The Nokia brand is recognized and trusted around the world. When someone attempts to register a mark that we believe may lead to confusion or dilution of our brand, we take steps to protect our valuable asset," Nokia spokesman Mark Durrant said.
The developers from Brno claim that they did not think of the brand famous in the past for mobile phones when creating the warehouse program. According to the CCV, Loki's designation is based on the Latin name for a type of dragonfly, whose rapid movement is supposed to be analogous to the movement of storekeepers around a warehouse.
"On the Czech market, the possibility of confusion is unlikely. We sell modern cloud software, which companies use to equip their warehouse operations, and we are not really moving into the field of mobile phone production. And we do not want to be compared to a brand that may be losing steam in its field," he responded in E15 CCV manager Tomáš Kormaňák.
CCV filed for trademark protection with the Industrial Property Office in August before the program was launched. "She applied for protection for products and services belonging to class 9, 35 and 42, as the software belongs to class 9, the related services of business management in the warehouse belong to class 35 and the development of computer software to class 42 according to the international classification," said Ondrášek.
Nokia's objection is based on the fact that Nokia's earlier trade mark is valid in all classes of goods and services and thus covers the widest possible range of goods and services, and thus of course also overlaps in classes 9, 35 and 42. "CCV does not challenge the claim the objector, if it is a matter of agreement on these classes of products and services. In reality, however, these are completely different brands aimed at other target groups," said Ondrášek.
According to E15, a trademark dispute can last months and complicate the company's operations.
