Developer Dušan Kunovský and architect Josef Pleskot in a TV interview on the occasion of the Architecture and Development Summit, however, gave other, not so "rosy" figures. For example, the Czech Republic ranks 154th in the world in the speed of construction procedures. It may happen that the current economic "boom" will not leave behind any significant architectural heritage as it was in the past.
The biggest obstacle is not only existing legislation, but also a slow, inefficient bureaucracy. This is also documented by comparative studies, in which the Czech Republic significantly lags behind developed countries in the overall quality and performance of public administration.
Our country has simply not been able to make good use of the potential of the good economic situation of recent years to invest in the future. It is nice that salaries and pensions are increasing, but people with an improving standard of living will also want to have a place to live, to travel in a modern and fast way, to have quality cultural stands, to live without an unbearable environmental burden.
But in the capital city of Prague, for example, it has not been possible to complete the inner and outer ring road or to build a high-speed rail or metro to the airport for years. And Prague doesn't even have a modern, architecturally bold national library, concert hall, or national gallery. The reason is not only the absurd scramble for architectural competitions, spatial plans and building permits, but also a kind of specifically Czech conservatism, which adheres to the motto "every bolder change is for the worse".
And when it seems that something more daring could be done, it will almost certainly be thwarted by preservationists or other rather foolish associations or politicians. In the absurd drama surrounding Jan Kaplický's "blob" designed for the new building of the National Library, President Václav Klaus even wanted to tie himself to the diggers.
