Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to see if it can hold cryptocurrencies. This is in response to an instruction from the state-owned company Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which seeks to be able to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank, and for the bank to then pay the oil company's suppliers in cryptocurrencies. Staff are also studying a proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies in foreign reserves, which are now near a 30-year low. This was reported by Bloomberg, citing information from four sources.
Sanctions imposed by the United States against the authoritarian regime of President Nicolás Maduro have largely cut off Venezuela from the global financial system. This further deepened the country's economic crisis. However, the current crisis is one of the most serious in the world, which has forced officials to use a mixture of different ways to move money. While Maduro's bid to launch the world's first state-owned cryptocurrency failed, ongoing efforts to use digital currencies show how desperate the government is to find ways around the restrictions.
Neither Venezuela's central bank nor PDVSA responded to a request for comment.
It is not clear how PDVSA came to own bitcoins and ethers, or how much value of these currencies it owns. The business is struggling to get payments from customers through conventional channels because big banks are unwilling to do business with entities that are subject to sanctions. Last month, the firm received most of the $700 million (CZK 16.6 billion) payment in Chinese yuan as the parties failed to find financial institutions to facilitate the transaction.
PDVSA may be reluctant to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market, as that would require it to register on an exchange and undergo due diligence. Instead, he wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank to pay entities that PDVSA owes. Representatives of the oil company believe that the central bank is less exposed to possible obstacles that could arise when paying with cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized internet ledger known as blockchain to verify and record transactions. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are possible without the need for an intermediary. Few banks are involved in digital currencies because of the money laundering and customer information issues associated with them, complicating compliance.
After the debacle of 2018, cryptocurrencies are seeing a return to prominence this year thanks to expectations of greater institutional adoption and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain unstable. Bitcoin is down nearly 20 percent over the past four days, but has gained about 130 percent since the beginning of the year.
