Appendix No. 6 / Project management methodology
1. Project Charter
1.1 The purpose of the Project Charter is to define the formal management processes and the method of communication between the parties in order to fulfill the subject of the Agreement so that the execution of the work or the provision of services is in accordance with the Agreement and this Project Management Methodology. The Project Charter makes available to persons involved in the execution of the work or the provision of services those parts of the Agreement that are necessary to fulfill its purpose. The project charter determines the occupation of the organizational structure of the project, the method of communication, control and escalation mechanisms and the structure of the project portal, on which all documentation related to the execution of the work or the provision of services is archived. The project charter will be drawn up by the project leaders and approved by the Steering Committee.
2. Organizational structure of the project
2.1 The organizational components of the Project are (1) the Project Steering Committee (hereinafter referred to as "SCP") and (2) the Project Management of the Project (hereinafter referred to as "PVP") and (3) work teams. SCP and PVP are permanent organizational components of the project. Work teams are temporary project organizational components.
3. Steering committee
3.1 Powers of the SCP / Steering committee of the project in particular:
3.1.1 approves the Project Charter; and further
3.1.2 resolves escalated issues that have not been resolved at the PVP level; and further
3.1.3 solves issues with an impact on the scope of work performed or services provided; and further
3.1.4 solves issues related to the delivery schedule; and further
3.1.5 resolves issues related to remuneration or remuneration structure for services provided or work performed; and further
3.1.6 accepts individual deliveries, services, parts of the work or the work as a whole; and further
3.2 Members of the SCP / On behalf of the Client, members of the SCP are (1) the business project sponsor and (2) the director of the ISIT division and (3) the project manager. On behalf of the Contractor, SCP members are (1) the management representative and (2) the project manager.
3.3 SCP meetings / The SCP meets at least once per quarter. The exact days on which the SCP meets regularly will be determined by the project manager in the Project Charter. The SCP always meets during the evaluation of a significant milestone in the delivery schedule (e.g. the start or end of the acceptance procedure). The SCP meets whenever a project leader calls for a SCP meeting. The SCP meets at the Customer's headquarters.
3.4 SCP meeting program / The SCP meeting program and documents that will be the subject of discussion will be delivered to SCP members by the project manager on behalf of the Contractor, at least 3 working days before the SCP meeting. At its meeting, the SCP always discusses the report on the status of the project and drafts of minutes related to the acceptance of delivery, services or work.
3.5 The right to invite experts and advisers / If one party considers it necessary, it has the right to invite experts or advisers to the SCP meeting, but it will inform the other party in advance and at the same time state the reasons why the presence of experts or advisers at the SCP meeting is expedient.
3.6 Voting / After discussing each agenda item, SCP members vote on the proposal submitted for the relevant agenda item. Each SCP member has one vote.
3.7 SCP decision with an impact on the contractual terms / If the SCP decision concerns the contractual terms under which work is performed or services are provided, especially if the SCP decision has an impact on the remuneration for which work is performed or services are provided, the Customer without undue delay after acceptance such a decision, will prepare an addendum to the contract in question.
3.8 Minutes / From the meeting of the SCP, the project manager prepares minutes on behalf of the Client, which he delivers to the project manager on behalf of the Contractor.
4. Project management of the project
4.1 Powers of PVP / Project management of the project in particular:
4.1.1 checks all outputs of individual phases of work execution or service provision; and further
4.1.2 evaluates and refines the schedule of deliveries and the progress of work when performing work or providing services; and further
4.1.3 discusses changes that do not affect the wording of the Agreement; and further
4.1.4 manages cooperation between the Customer and the Contractor; and further
4.1.5 manage the risks and corrective measures related to the performance of the work or the provision of services; and further
4.1.6 escalates to an SCP meeting.
4.2 PVP members / On behalf of the Customer, the PVP members are (1) the project manager and (2) the main business analyst and (3) the application architect. For the Contractor, the PVP members are (1) the project manager and (2) the chief analyst and (3) the chief architect.
4.3 Meetings The SCP / PVP meets once a week, at the Customer's headquarters or through remote communication.
4.4 PVP meeting program and materials / The PVP meeting program and materials that will be the subject of discussion will be delivered to the PVP members by the project manager on behalf of the Contractor, at least 1 working day before the PVP meeting. At its PVP meeting, it always discusses:
4.4.1 fulfillment of open tasks from previous PVP; and
4.4.2 the course of performance of work or provision of services; and
4.4.3 fulfillment and updating of the work schedule; and
4.4.4 identified problems and the method of solving them; and
4.4.5 plan for further action; and
4.4.6 risks related to the performance of work or the provision of services; and
4.4.7 evaluation and other requirements for cooperation of the Customer; and
4.4.8 the status and severity of outstanding defects or incidents; and
4.4.9 change requests; and
4.5 The right to invite experts and advisers / If their presence is expedient for the effective course of negotiations, both parties have the right to invite experts and advisers or members of project teams to the PVP meeting.
4.6 Minutes / From the meeting of the PVP, the project manager prepares minutes on behalf of the Customer, which he delivers to the project manager on behalf of the Contractor.
5. Work teams
5.1 Work teams / Work teams consist of employees of the Customer or the Contractor and, where applicable, employees of third parties. In particular, the work teams (1) carry out specific parts of the work or the services provided and (2) provide the know-how necessary for the execution of the work or the provision of services and (3) provide material and professional data for further decision-making.
5.2 Roles in work teams / Assignment of roles is always adapted to the current stage of work execution or service provision. On the Customer's side, members of the work team consist of:
5.2.1 Business analysts of the subject area/areas
5.2.2 Guarantor / key user of the subject area/ areas
5.2.3 Technical and technological infrastructure specialist
On the side of the Contractor, the members of the work team are:
5.2.4 Chief consultant/analyst – architect of the proposed solution
5.2.5 Consultant/Analyst
5.2.6 Specialist for technical infrastructure
5.2.7 Developer
5.2.8 Tester, trainer
5.2.9 Operation and Installation Specialist
6. A complete overview of the assignment of individual project roles and their communication matrix is determined by the Project Charter. Rules of mutual communication
6.1 Management of communication / Communication in the project is mainly managed by the project manager. Communication is always conducted objectively with the aim of solving individual tasks as quickly and efficiently as possible. Mutual, controlled, communication of project teams mainly includes:
6.1.1 Project meetings (SCP, PVP, consultations, workshops, ...)
6.1.2 Acceptance and handover procedures
6.1.3 Transmission and storage of tasks, information and documents
6.1.4 Record of change requests
6.1.5 Records of defects and incidents
6.2 Project meetings - program and documents / The schedule and list of tasks from project meetings is always updated at the next meeting. The documents that will be the subject of the project meeting will be sent by the project manager to the participants of the meeting in advance according to the subject of the meeting. The documents are registered and updated on the project portal.
6.3 Minutes of project meetings / From each project meeting, the Customer's project manager shall prepare written minutes, which shall be delivered to the Contractor's project manager the following working day after the project meeting.
6.4 Amendments and additions to the minutes of the project meeting / Participants will make amendments and additions to the minutes of the project meeting within 2 working days from the date of delivery of the minutes. Negotiations on modifications and additions to the entry are managed by the project manager. Modifications and additions to the record are not the place to conduct a discussion. After incorporating modifications and additions, the Customer's project manager will close the minutes of the project meeting and save them on the project portal. The project leaders can change the deadline for comments on the minutes of the project meeting by agreement. If any comment period for the minutes of the project meeting elapses without comments from the meeting participants, the minutes are considered approved.
7. Risk management
7.1 Identification and registration of risks / During the execution of work or the provision of services, all parties involved identify and subsequently manage risks in a documented manner that may affect the quality of outputs or deadlines for the execution of work or the provision of services. Risks are registered by the project manager on the project portal, including their severity.
7.2 Discussion of risks at the PVP meeting / Discussion and evaluation of risks is a mandatory agenda item for every PVP meeting. The PVP meeting establishes measures to eliminate or minimize risks.
7.3 Escalation / If a disagreement occurs or if a risk is identified with a severity affecting the contractual arrangement or schedule or remuneration, such risk will be escalated by PVP to the SCP meeting.
8. Quality control
8.1 The basic tool for quality control of project outputs is the acceptance procedure. The subject of quality assurance is:
8.1.1 Checking the completeness of the subject of the work or provision of services so that the purpose of the contract is fulfilled
8.1.2 Evaluation and settlement of comments, defects and incidents so that the purpose of the contract is fulfilled
8.1.3 Checking the documentation up-to-date and complete
8.1.4 Control of adherence to the delivery schedule
8.1.5 Implementation of approved changes
8.1.6 Results of other agreed activities according to minutes of the meeting.
