Appendix No. 7 / Classification of incidents
The items below are for inspiration only. This appendix must be formulated precisely and comprehensively by the project manager.
Incidents from the operational environment
A Category A Incident means an Incident in an operational environment if, for example:
the user cannot log into the Application
when the Application repeatedly crashes at the same step and the user cannot complete a critical process
when the system shows too long (double the defined performance parameters)
responses to user activity
when it is not possible to print the documentation or report for the client
when incorrect data is displayed to the end customer
The critical functionalities/processes of the Application are:
account creation or cancellation
trigger the daily shutter
A category B incident means an incident in an operational environment if, for example:
the user's work is slowed down, but it does not seriously affect the adherence to the workflow
when non-critical functionality is unavailable to the end customer.
A category C incident means an incident in an operational environment if, for example:
when it comes to a language defect or a font other than the one agreed upon
when it is a graphical error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in using the interface
when it is a Documentation defect
Incidents from the acceptance environment
Incident category TA means Incident in the acceptance environment if, for example:
it is not possible to create a client in the system
Incident category TB means Incident in the acceptance environment if, for example:
It is not possible to change some parameters of the client's account
Incident category TC means Incident in the acceptance environment if, for example:
when it comes to a language defect or a font other than the one agreed upon
when it is a graphical error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in using the interface
when it is a Documentation defect
