The traditionally much-watched fight for the fastest man on the planet will be the hunt for defending silver medalist Christian Coleman at the World Championships. The 23-year-old American is the leader of the world charts with a time of 9.81 seconds and has only lost once this year. However, his start at the top of the season was in jeopardy due to the case of missed doping tests.
The United States Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) closed his case in early September without filing charges due to formal reasons. Coleman did not pass three doping tests last year and this year, but not within 12 months. The World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) dated his first offense back to April 1, 2018, i.e. to the beginning of the second quarter, but he missed the test itself only on June 6. And because the third omission occurred on April 29, 2019, Coleman was not guilty of three missed checks in 12 months.
Coleman argued that he simply forgot to update the data on the app about the athletes' whereabouts. "I don't take drugs, I don't take anything legal. A lot of athletes use legal creatine or protein powder or various other supplements for faster recovery. And I don't take anything, I work hard and that's it," he said before the start of the WC.
He suffered the only defeat out of six starts this year at the 100 at the start of the season at the Diamond League in Shanghai, where compatriot Noah Lyles surpassed him by just six thousandths of a second. He used Coleman's absence to triumph in the Diamond League final, but will only run the 200 at the World Cup.
On paper, the second fastest competitor is the 22-year-old Nigerian Divine Oduduru with a performance of 9.86, but he has only been successful in American university competitions so far.
The 37-year-old American Justin Gatlin, who flashed a time of 9.87 in Stanford in June, will defend the title. However, he ran the last 100 in Zagreb in just 10.29, because he slightly injured his hamstring.
South African Akani Simbine, three-time Olympic medalist from Rio Andre de Grasse and European champion Zharnel Hughes are also among the favorites. The fastest Jamaican is 2011 world champion Yohan Blake with a time of 9.96.
The men's 100 will start on Friday with the preliminary round and heats. The semi-finals and finals are scheduled for Saturday. The medal race will take place at 21:15 CEST.
