Epilepsy complicated his love of sports, thanks to the operation he has new hope
Honzík's parents first noticed that something was wrong with him when he was a year and a half old. He always stared into space for several minutes, became motionless and did not respond to anyone. The pediatrician therefore sent him to a children's neurology clinic, where the doctors, after a series of examinations, diagnosed him with epilepsy and immediately put him on medication, but it did not work immediately.
It took almost a year for doctors to find the perfect combination of drugs that made him stop having seizures completely. At the age of five, the doctors stopped his medication, and since the seizures did not return, his parents assumed that Honza was healthy and began to encourage him to do more sports. He rode a bike, skied, played tennis and floorball, spent his free time playing games with his sister and friends. But at the age of eleven he had another seizure and everything started anew.
The doctors tried different combinations of drugs again, but this time nothing worked, the seizures in the form of absences kept recurring. Since Honzo always lost consciousness during a seizure, the parents were terrified that he would get it while playing sports and get injured. Gradually, Honza stopped riding a bicycle and exchanged downhill skis for cross-country skis and a snowboard. Although the sport gave him fits from time to time, he never completely gave it up. He even fulfilled his dream and finished the Spartan Race, but together with a friend who kept an eye on him to help in case of emergency.
When Honzo was 15 years old, his parents decided to try to change doctors and turned to specialists at the General Hospital in Motola. After a series of examinations, the doctors there decided that Honza was a candidate for surgery to remove the tumor from his brain - the source of epileptic seizures. "I had to undergo 2 operations in a row, first the doctors inserted probes into my brain that sensed its activity, then they were able to remove the bearing. It was a few weeks of hell for me. I just had to lie down and hardly move, wires were sticking out of my head , which were connected to the computer," recalls Honza.
The operation was successful, and the doctors removed the rather extensive deposit. "The first days after the operation, it was very mentally demanding, Honza was apathetic, confused, sad and almost did not speak. Compared to how lively and communicative he is normally, it was a scary change, but luckily everything returned to normal after a few days," he describes mom and adds: "He had 1 seizure a month and a half after the surgery, but according to the doctors it happens. He has been seizure free for 3 months since then."
This school year, Honza will graduate, in addition to sports, he enjoys languages and has started working with Company E, with whom he goes to schools for talks about epilepsy. Honza is not fully involved in sports activities yet, he is slowly returning to sports. "I'm learning how to do sports correctly, how to breathe well, so as not to expose my body to sudden stress, which is quite a challenge with my competitive nature," explains Honza.
This year, therefore, he will not actively participate in the traditional EPPI paddling triathlon, in which patients with epilepsy and healthy athletes meet, and which takes place this weekend, September 28, 2019, at Veselská pískovna. But maybe next year.
