At first glance, it's nothing complicated.
Most nouns in Czech express only one grammatical gender, so it is not a problem to determine whether they are masculine, feminine or neuter.
But then there is also a relatively large group of nouns whose gender is not fixed.
Such nouns fluctuate between two genders.
When inflected, they acquire double endings and in some cases remain in the uninflected form.
For example, the words "svízel" and "hip" are both masculine and feminine, in the former they are inflected according to the pattern of "machine", in the latter according to the pattern of "song".
Another group of nouns has different forms already in the first case of the singular, for example: "rádek/rádka", "kedluben/kodlubna" or "brambor/potato" (in the sense of food).
Both forms are literary, have the same meaning, and are therefore freely interchangeable.
Some expressions may differ regionally, for example "okurka" in Bohemia and "okurek" in Moravia, but in this case the Moravian variant is unwritten, as are other Czech-Moravian pairs of words: "příkop" and "príkopa", " donut" and "doughnut" etc.
Some words that entered Czech from other languages were originally uninflected, but they gradually adopted Czech endings.
A typical example is the expression "image", which is both masculine and feminine, or the word "buffet", which remained uninflected in the neuter, but in the masculine has endings following the pattern of "castle".
Civilization on borrowed time
Recently, I remembered a beautiful "message" from one of Šimek's great stories with Grossmann, which takes place partly in a cemetery, which goes like this: "I warned her that she cries well, but on someone else's grave!" It occurred to me that many world politicians engaged in the senseless fight against climate change are behaving very similarly now.
They act as if humans rule planet earth. In reality, we are just a speck on her surface, which she can blow away with her immense powers like a strong gust of wind a candle flame. Probably few of them watch the famous British and American science documentaries discussing the destructive capabilities of our blue ball. After all, it would be enough for one of the larger active volcanoes to really "crack up" and our advanced civilization would be ruined.
And it is highly likely to happen in the near future. According to leading volcanologists, a number of large volcanoes are "charged and unlocked" (for example, Katla in Iceland).
In a way, it would be ideal if that eruption, if it had to happen, happened as soon as possible. Even before trillions of dollars are completely wasted on measures aimed at reducing the production of carbon dioxide, because any really angry volcano can release it, together with dust and poisonous volcanic gases, into the atmosphere at least a hundred times more than was saved at the expense of the inhabitants of Europe.
It therefore makes no sense to forcefully limit CO2 production. In addition, it has been scientifically proven that with its significantly higher proportion in the air, plants form more biological matter and are also more resistant to drought. For humanity, possible warming is significantly more favorable than, for example, a rapid return of the ice age.
If we realize the still insufficiently researched influence of the solar cycles on the Earth's climate, we have to come to only one reasonable conclusion: Let's try hard to keep the Earth as clean as possible and try to adapt to the other changes, which we cannot cope with forcefully, with the least possible cost!
