Autotuner brought the voice of the digital soul
Everything you know about obesity is wrong, reads the headline of a long piece written for the Huffington Post by Michael Hobbes and photographed by Finlay Mackay. In a provocative explanation, it is written that the medical community ignored the facts about obesity for decades and waged a merciless (and also unnecessary) war against overweight people, which not only affected public opinion, but also destroyed many lives. But now is the time for a new paradigm.
What Hobbes states at the outset is the fact that there is often a very long and tedious journey from knowing and knowing facts to putting them into practice. He mentions the case of scurvy, when some captains already in the seventeenth century distributed lemons, limes and oranges to their crew in the belief that they would prevent the disease. However, the British Navy abandoned this practice due to concerns about increased costs. The clear influence of the fruit in the prevention and treatment of the disease was then proven in the middle of the 18th century, but it took another fifty years before the navy took it into account. Even seat belts existed long before the invention of the car, but they only became mandatory in the 1960s, and the first confirmed asbestos-related death dates back to 1906, yet its first ban came in 1973.
"Every discovery in public health—no matter how important—has always had to compete with traditions, prejudices, and financial incentives within the society into which it was to be implemented," Hobbes writes. In American society today, almost 80 percent of the adult population and about one third of children meet the definition of overweight or obese. More Americans are living with obesity today than breast cancer, Alzheimer's, Parkinson's and HIV combined.
At the same time, obesity is seen as a supremely personal failure of the individual, which is claimed to burden the healthcare system and reduce GDP. The fear of being fat is so great in the population that Americans today spend more money on diets than they spend on computer games and movies. However, the truth is that diets don't work. Already in 1959, research showed that 95 to 98% of attempts to lose weight end in failure, and two-thirds of dieters subsequently gain more weight than they lost.
Armed with statistics, Hobbes goes on to describe the lifestyles and traumas of overweight people. Here, the personal meets the systemic, when, for example, at the faculties, when teaching future doctors, only 19 hours of the entire course are devoted to the issue of nutrition. Which at a time when 60 percent of the calories Americans consume comes from ultra-processed food.
How obesity is stigmatized is illustrated by reports from surgeries where overweight people typically experience shorter visits, are treated with less empathy by doctors, and are seen as more problematic patients.
However, obesity is far from just an American problem, as Hobbes writes. Since 1980, the proportion of obesity has doubled in 73 countries of the world and increased in 113. And during that time, no country has managed to reduce and stop this increase. Absolutely none.
