Crested macaques are so-called endemics of the island of Sulawesi, that is, they do not live anywhere else in the world in the wild. A typical feature is the black coat and crest on the head, which gives them their name. Crested macaques live in rainforests, mainly at lower altitudes.
Like most primates, they feed on plant and animal food. The menu is dominated by the fruits of forest trees, which are complemented by flowers and leaves. They meet their protein needs by eating small arthropods, larvae and, to a lesser extent, bird eggs and chicks.
"If we leave aside the natural enemies, which are pythons, everything else has been written down by man. Local residents hunt macaques as a favorite prey with tasty meat and for their fur. Burning and cutting down the rainforest is also fatal for these animals," added the spokeswoman .
