The museum in Semile returns to the velvet revolution with an exhibition
An imitation of a normalization room with a television showing footage of the brutal police intervention against students on November 17, 1989 in Prague. This is also in the new exhibition of the museum in Semile, which is devoted to the velvet revolution. "The basis is to present what happened in Semile after the events on Národní třída," said exhibition curator Tomáš Chvátal.
"I would say that the atmosphere was basically the same everywhere, with the fact that the first demonstration was held in Semily on November 22, and then every day more people were gradually arriving," he said. Among the most active from the beginning was a group of local dissidents around Miroslav Matěcha, who was the only one from the city and the immediate vicinity to sign Charter 77, and the Dědečkovys, who circulated the Several Sentences petition. According to Chvátal, the Civic Forum was also created relatively quickly. "One specific thing is that there was a very strong group of local doctors in the Civic Forum," said the curator.
About 50 photographs should draw visitors into the happenings in the city at that time, the pictures were taken 30 years ago by Karel Bárta. A video from the general strike on November 27, 1989, filmed by František Tomíček, has also been preserved and will be played on a loop throughout the duration of the exhibition. Ivan Hlas also spoke and sang at the demonstration. The Semil archive also lent a number of preserved banners from that time to the exhibition. "On them was: Let's not get drunk on a roll, From trough to trough, We don't want violence," said Chvátal. Some of the changes in the city were very quick at the time, for example already in December, people decided in a nationwide vote that the square would be Riegrovo and canceled the previous name Gottwaldovo.
The exhibition also captures the events before the November events. "In the first part, we present to witnesses and students what happened before, such a late normalization. I think we managed to collect unique documents from Semil, whether they are banners with various communist slogans or a bronze plate from the museum of the workers' movement at the time," said Chvátal . One room is meant to evoke the feeling of what it might have looked like in the living room of an ordinary household back then.
The last part of the exhibition is dedicated to what happened after the Velvet Revolution. It is focused on the first free elections. "We wallpapered one room with election posters. Those who experienced it will remember the posters With us to Europe or Václav Klaus is still there under the banner of OF with the beautiful motto Everyone for his community," added the curator.
