The launch of the new toll is not threatened, reports the Kremlin. But there is a change of operator in the game
On Friday, the Ministry of Transport started preparations for a new tender for the operation of the new toll system. It is a back-up plan that the state would use in the event that the current toll contract is legally cancelled. In addition, the state is also preparing another provisional solution in case the tender is not completed on time. Transport Minister Vladimír Kremlík (for ANO) stated this on Facebook.
On Thursday, the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS) banned the implementation of the toll contract between the state and the CzechToll/SkyToll consortium, with a one-year delay. The Ministry will file an appeal against this.
"The launch of the new toll collection system is not at risk. Starting today, we are starting the preparation of a new transparent procurement procedure, the subject of which will be the services of operating the new toll system, which is now being completed by the CzechToll and SkyToll consortium," said the minister.
The state would thus be looking for the operator of the toll currently being prepared, which will be launched from this December, in the tender. It would therefore not be a competition for a completely new toll system, as was the case with the last tender, nor the use of the old system now operated by Kapsch.
However, according to the Kremlin, the ministry is also preparing for the fact that it would not have time to prepare the new tender in time. "Based on previous experience with the course of the toll tender, I am deeply convinced that the ÚOHS is wrong and that it is objectively impossible to prepare and implement such a complex procurement procedure and hand over the operation of the toll system to a new operator within the period of 12 months set by it," he said.
In addition to the new procurement procedure, the resort will also prepare a provisional solution that would solve the collection of tolls for a temporary period until the state finds a full-fledged solution.
Apparently, the state will not yet use the offer that the current toll administrator Kapsch presented to it in recent days. The Austrian company offered the state the operation of the existing system in case the toll contract was cancelled.
At the same time, the Kremlin reiterated that it believes that a backup plan will not be needed. The Ministry will therefore file an appeal against the decision of the Antimonopoly Office.
On Thursday, the ÚOHS issued a decision in which it prohibited the performance of the toll contract. However, the ban will only come into effect one year after the authority's decision becomes legal. This is not valid and an appeal against it can be filed with the chairman of the office. The Ministry and CzechToll are therefore continuing to prepare the new toll, which should be launched in December.
In last year's tender for the new toll system and its operator, the CzechToll/SkyToll consortium won. It succeeded in the toll tender with an offer of 10.75 billion crowns for ten years of operation. The current operator Kapsch protested against the course of the tender and the validity of the toll contract, which failed in the competition with an offer of over 13 billion crowns.
