Šafránková threw 65.46 meters on her third attempt and was almost six meters short of her best this year, which she would have to improve to advance. Maláčová jumped 435 cm, 450 cm was already beyond her strength. To participate in the final, the limit of 460 cm had to be overcome.
Mezuliáníková, who got to the championship only at the last moment thanks to an invitation from the international federation IAAF, finished in the fourth run in the penultimate sixth place, and even her time of 2:03.48 minutes was not enough for her to advance to the semi-finals. She fell short of her best this year by one and a half seconds. "It was quite fast for me, unfortunately I was fighting with my opponent in the corner, which took a lot of my strength. I thought I still had the strength, but it slowed me down there. I almost stopped and had to start again, so in this one was a little uncomfortable. I can't be completely satisfied," said the Czech representative.
She was happy that she overtook at least one rival in the finish line. "She really wasn't doing well, so every defeated opponent was good. But I think it was for the fifth place. Unfortunately," she added. Winnie Nanyonda of Uganda was the fastest half-distance runner in the heats in 2:00.36.
In Doha, the best octogenarian of recent years, Caster Semenya from South Africa, is missing. She has too high a level of testosterone in her body, but like some other runners, she refuses the treatment that is required by the IAAF rules starting this year.
In the 100-meter races, the American Christian Coleman confirmed his role as the number one favorite, who with a time of 9.98 was the only one to break under ten seconds. His compatriot Justin Gatlin, who is trying to defend his title at the age of 37, also advanced to the semi-finals. The Nigerian Divine Oduduru, who is number two in this year's tables with a performance of 9.86, did not start, and his fight with Coleman, who has a performance of 9.81 this season, was expected.
Cuban Juan Miguel Echevarría already showed great form in the long distance qualification, who reached a distance of 840 cm with his first jump. No athlete has jumped that far in World Championship qualification in the last 20 years. The 21-year-old Cuban leads this year's charts with a performance of 865 cm.
The Slovenians also defeated the Polish world champions and are in the finals of the EC
Slovenian volleyball players will sensationally play for the premier title of European champions. With the support of almost 12,000 boisterous fans in Ljubljana, they beat the reigning two-time world champions Poles 3:1 and are the first finalists.
Who they challenge in Sunday's climax in Paris will be decided on Friday between France and Serbia.
The Slovenian team was much more compact than the Polish world champions in the semi-finals. They only had the beginning of the opening set and, with luck, the end of the second set, but the home volleyball players excelled in defense and of the players in the red and white jersey, only León, a native of Cuba, scored points.
On the other hand, in the home line-up, both smashers Čebulj and Urnaut, as well as the second all-rounder Štern, who soon replaced the lackluster Gasparini, were in top form. The Poles paid for the fact that they had won all their previous games at this Euro, while the Slovenians were gaining confidence after tough play-off battles with Bulgaria and Russia.
In August of this year, the Slovenians lost 1:3 to the Poles in the Olympic qualification in Gdańsk, but they avenged their defeat at home. But now Stožica will leave the sold-out Ljubljana arena. After today, however, they have a certain second medal in history, in Paris they can improve on the unexpected silver from the EC four years ago.
At the previous European championship, the Slovenians finished eighth, only behind the Czech national team.
