Jan Šindelář's comment: Managing railways as a company
Heaven's election, although apparently not completely smooth, is the culmination of a sad story about the inability of the state to give a clear direction to the roads. The board of directors has been incomplete for over a year, and even after Wednesday evening, that did not change, as one of the members resigned. The provisional lasts.
The selection procedure itself was a farce from the beginning, already because the requirements for candidates, especially in the field of practice, were significantly eased. Compared to last year's selection, the requirements for the size of the company in which the candidate was supposed to work in the past have been reduced. At first, the members of the selection committee and then the supervisory board only played the role of pimps.
Nebeský probably presented the weakest professional resume of the five finalists, yet without experience from a large company, he beat experienced fighters from the management of logistics giants and transport companies. The participation of interesting managers from the private sector was probably the brightest side (and the greatest hope) of the whole process. Today, those in question already know that they only played the role of narrative backdrops in a political game.
Maybe Nebesky will surprise, show great talent and end up being the best lane boss ever. At least in the beginning, however, it will be accompanied by the aftertaste of political tabloids. České dráhy does not have an easy time ahead, they have to cope with competition during the liberalization of the market and with a lack of employees in operation. Train drivers, shifters and mechanics are missing. What motivation are they supposed to have for further work and respect for management when the state behaves like an elephant in china in the top management?
The second important group are creditors. We will see how they interpret the games at the head of the railways next spring, when the railways defend their rating. What is certain is that lenders perceive instability. It is sad that every year someone else goes to the Moody's agency to defend the rating on behalf of Czech Railways. The agency did not miss the frequent changes in railway management and the political influence on the company, it criticized them already this summer.
Among other things, the ANO movement is coining the slogan that the state must be managed like a company. For a start, it would be enough if one large state-owned company was managed as a company, and not as a state. Czech Railways is still one of the largest companies in the country, and it would be good if it were led by the best. They reported, but the state despised them. It can certainly be argued that the post at the head of the railways has always been a political matter. But then we can forgive ourselves the antics with the selection process.
