Microplastics found their way into human intestines, a study confirmed for the first time
The scientists' suspicions of several years have been confirmed. A team led by Professor Philipp Schwabl of the University of Vienna has published a study that proves the presence of microplastics in human feces for the first time. Although the study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia, small plastic particles between 50 and 500 micrometers in size were found in the samples of all the people examined. None of the eight subjects were vegetarians, six of them did not avoid marine fish, all drank water from plastic bottles and food wrapped in plastic.
And it would actually be a bit of a miracle if nothing was found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example for the needs of the cosmetics industry, or are created by the breakdown of larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and sodas; in short, everywhere on the planet. Thus, their entry into the human digestive system has only been officially confirmed. There were roughly 20 microplastic particles per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them.
Of course, lay and scientific awareness knows that this is not good. However, humanity still does not know how bad it is - and what effect microplastics have on "host" organisms. Small particles can reach the bloodstream or the lymphatic system and end up, for example, in the liver. "This is the first study of its kind and it confirms what we have long thought. Now that we have the first evidence of microplastics in the human body, we need to continue to investigate exactly what this means for human health," says Schwabl.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the intestines can negatively affect the immune responses of the digestive system, thereby facilitating the absorption of toxic chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far, there is no known solution other than to limit the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. However, this will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will at least be to stop its steep increase. As far as plastic bottles are concerned, experts estimate that in three years humanity will consume a fifth more of them than today. The current pace is a staggering million bottles bought per minute. About eight million tons of plastic end up in the seas and oceans every year. Litter threatens marine ecosystems and contaminates the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some countries have already taken steps towards restrictions and other measures, Kenya for example - under the threat of draconian punishments - has banned plastic bags. The European Commission is considering minor bans (a well-known straw), and the domestic Ministry of the Environment is heading in the same direction. Critics, however, claim that such measures are nice, but completely insufficient.
